The National Memorial to the Algerian War and the Combats in Morocco and Tunisia, located in Paris, is a monument that honors French soldiers who fought in the Algerian War, in Tunisia and in Morocco. The Memorial consists of a large bronze sculpture and many plaques with the names of the fallen soldiers. It is a place of silence and reflection. The ambiance is elegant and respectful, and the sculpture is imposing and moving. The visit is an opportunity to understand and remember the history of France and the sacrifices of its soldiers. I recommend visiting this memorial at night as the lighting is very beautiful and creates a beautiful contrast with the Eiffel Tower in the background. For those who are interested in history and want to pay tribute to French soldiers, it is worth visiting.

The National Monument to the Algerian War and the Fighting in Morocco and Tunisia in Paris is a monument honoring French soldiers who fought in the Algerian War in Tunisia and Morocco. The memorial consists of a large bronze sculpture and many plaques with the names of fallen soldiers. It is a place of silence and reflection. The ambience is elegant and respectful, the sculpture impressive and moving. The visit is an opportunity to understand and remember the history of France and the sacrifices of its soldiers. For example, the first column in blue shows, year by year and alphabetically, the names of the 23,000 soldiers who died between 1954 and 1962 for Algeria and between 1952 and 1956 for Morocco and Tunisia. A poignant moment to remember these men.  I recommend visiting this monument at night as the lighting is very beautiful and creates a nice contrast with the Eiffel Tower in the background.

The Evian agreements are the result of negotiations between representatives of France and those of the Provisional Government of the Algerian Republic (GPRA) formed by the National Liberation Front (FLN) during the Algerian war. These agreements were signed on March 18, 1962 in Evian and translated into an immediate ceasefire applied to the entire Algerian territory. These agreements ended eight years of a war that still had no name and for which France had deployed some 400,000 soldiers and during which between 250,000 and 400,000 Algerians died (more than a million according to the FLN). . On March 19 at 12 noon the application of the agreements signed the day before in Evian between the French government and the Provisional Government of the Algerian Republic comes into force. It was the official end to eight years of colonial war in Algeria. However, on the same day that the Agreement came into force, both the FLN and the OAS broke it, killing a large number of people. In France there are 30,000 dead and 250,000 injured.

Worth seeing, but you need to know the meaning of the columns before visiting this monument. The first column in blue: displays year by year and alphabetically the names and first names of the 23,000 soldiers who died between 1954 and 1962 for Algeria and from 1952 to 1956 for Morocco and Tunisia. The second column in white: displays messages and the names of those who died and disappeared after the date of the ceasefire on March 19, 1962, in particular civilian victims and auxiliaries of the French army. The third column in red: dependent on an interactive terminal allows you to carry out searches and display the name of a deceased person on this display area. On the esplanade in front of the columns is engraved: "To the memory of the fighters who died for France during the Algerian war and the combats in Morocco and Tunisia, and to that of all the members of the auxiliary forces, killed afterwards ceasefire and many of which have not been identified. ¬ª

We can see on the three columns, through blue, white and red luminous displays, the names of the 23,000 French soldiers and harkis killed during the war, which start from the ground and fly towards the sky. The 3rd column is equipped with a terminal which allows us to find a particular name.  These three 6 meter high columns were inaugurated in 2002 by President Jacques Chirac, himself a second lieutenant in Algeria at the end of the 1950s.
